{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"39f56e86-9511-4435-b50e-9641961feb70","content":"On macOS, when a NativeAOT app crashes without `createdump`, you have two options:\n\n1. **Apple Crash Reports** – macOS automatically generates `.ips` crash reports in:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These contain the stack trace, signal info, and thread state.\n\n2. **Core dumps** – Enable them with:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n   Then reproduce the crash. Core files typically land in `/cores/core.<pid>`. You can inspect them with `lldb`:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./your-app\n   ```\n\nCheck the `DiagnosticReports` folder first — it's the easiest path since macOS generates reports automatically with no setup required.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"390b1bb1-8f85-4cac-9cec-5010ce52214e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT app on macOS when `createdump` isn't available. This is a general knowledge question - I don't need to search any codebase for this.","outputTokens":263,"requestId":"6816:12F0D5:C5435A:D2B2FB:6A0B0097"},"id":"2db217dc-b0f5-4486-a1f1-6755f00da47f","timestamp":"2026-05-18T12:05:51.942Z","parentId":"b9e8f3bb-a2d3-4294-8be0-784962524c7f"}
